Venus: the Epicureans believed not at all in the influence ot the Divine over the affairs of men. Why, then, does Lucretius begin his poem with an invocation to Venus? The question is not an easy one to answer. It was the custom oi the poets to preiace any important work with an address to the gods or some particular divinity lor inspiration. Prose writers, too, sometimes followed their example. Varro opens the ‘De Re Rustica· with a labored prayer to the gods oi the iarmer. Whatever may have been the motive of such invo- cations at first, aiter the decline oi the old religion in Greece and Rome to educated readers and hearers they no longer suggested any thought of the real presence ol the Divine; they furuished merely an occasion ior the dignified display oi a bit of literary finery. Hence the spiritless invocation of Ovid at the beginning oi the Metamor- phoses; instances of the like, with many others, some graceiul and some dull, may be found in the writings oi his contemporaries and the poets ot the decline. Oi similar character is Lucretius’ address to Calliope, quoted above. But while Lucretius in thus opening bis poem was coniorming to the example of the poets from Homer to Ennius, with him it was not a matter oi display or trifling.
